<div class="body-title">
  What is it used for?
</div>

<div class="body">
  <ul>
    <li>acting as a binder, stabilizer, and thickener</li>
    <li>helping to create a uniform texture in food products</li>
    <li>replacing some fats</li>
    <li>creating a creamy texture</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="body-title">
  May be found in...
</div>

<div class="body">
  <ul>
    <li>baked goods</li>
    <li>dressings</li>
    <li>ice cream</li>
    <li>frozen desserts</li>
    <li>confections</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="body-title">
  Dosage
</div>

<div class="body">
The recommended acceptable daily intake (ADI) of xanthan gum is 0–10 milligrams per kilogram each day.
It has a laxative effect when taken at doses of 15 milligrams or more.
<br><br>
Xanthan gum is not recommended for infants.


</div>

<div class="body-title">
  Health Benefits
</div>
<div class="body">
  <ul>
    <li>Can replace gluten</li>
    <li>Laxative effects</li>
    <li>Making liquids thicker and easier to swallow</li>
    <li>Stabilizing blood sugar levels when mixed with beta-glucan</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="body-title">
  Potential side effects...
</div>
<div class="body">
  <ul>
    <li>laxative effect</li>
    <li>Increase in flatulence or gas</li>
    <li>Necrotizing enterocolitis in infants</li>
    <li>Changes in gut bacteria</li>
  </ul>
</div>

